	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">psycopathicteen wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I wonder if the majority of developers made their SNES workstation using the &quot;almighty&quot; 68000.</div><br />A lot of them did <em>de facto</em>, since the Amigas they (European SNES devs) did graphics &amp; assembly on contained 68000s.<br /><br />However, others used regular PC-compatibles with a PDS system.<br /><br />Over in Japan, could be anything.  Enix used these: <br /><img src="http://www.chrismcovell.com/secret/weekly/HowVidGames31.jpg" alt="Image" /><img src="http://www.chrismcovell.com/secret/weekly/HowVidGames35.jpg" alt="Image" /><img src="http://www.chrismcovell.com/secret/weekly/HowVidGames43c.jpg" alt="Image" /><img src="http://www.chrismcovell.com/secret/weekly/HowVidGames35a.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />Sharp X68000s for graphics, regular PCs(?) with a Super Famicom Dev Unit for programming/burning.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


